The first phase of combat behavior involved mainly the very long forelegs of males, that were used to quickly knock over the opponent, without contact of the frontal horns (
Fig. 22
). The effect of such knocks apparently is only dissuasive because the dense hair pads on the ventral surface of the tarsal segments do not permit any kind of injury.

When the female was receptive, the male adopted a head to head position and surrounded the female and the twig with all its legs, holding each tarsus or tibia of the female with his legs before the extrusion of the parameres (
Fig. 24
). Copulation took place in this position for 3–5 min. Apparently, the male does not protect the female against other copulatory events afterwords.
